{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Generated function signature matches expected interface from the natural-language spec.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Slot A: \"generated function signature matches the expected interface ... specified in the description.\" Slot B: model-output boundary (correctness depends on what the real LLM emits). Slot C: if lowered to Integration with stubbed outputs, you can miss real cases where the model returns wrong parameter names/types while orchestration still passes. Rejection gate: Workflow was considered but rejected because this behavior only requires evaluating one generation output, not multiple agentic decisions in sequence.","test_description":"Run real LLM generation for interface-constrained prompts, parse emitted signature, and assert parameter names/types/return type match the expected interface; repeat over a small fixed prompt set to expose model-output failures.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.0,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow":0.12}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Orchestration runs attempts in order and exits immediately on first passing attempt.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Slot A: \"executes attempts in order and returns immediately on the first passing attempt.\" Slot B: handoff/state boundary across orchestrator, generator client, and test-result handling. Slot C: if lowered to Unit, you can miss cross-module wiring bugs (e.g., attempt index/bookkeeping mismatch causing an extra call after a pass). Integration-brake: no real OS/network/subprocess required; no dependence on model output quality; no multi-step agentic decision required.","test_description":"Wire orchestrator with deterministic stub generator + stub test executor that fail then pass; assert call order, attempt numbers, and that no third call occurs after first pass.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For tasks where one-shot generation usually fails, the live iterative loop can still pass within allowed attempts.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"Slot A: \"live iterative loop can still produce a passing implementation within the allowed attempts.\" Slot B: multi-step agentic boundary (generate -> test -> refine -> regenerate with real model decisions). Slot C: if lowered to Agentic (single-call focus), you can miss failures where cross-attempt feedback propagation/replanning breaks even though isolated calls look fine.","test_description":"Use a known prompt where first live attempt commonly fails; run full loop with real LLM and real test feedback, assert eventual pass occurs within <=3 attempts and record attempt-by-attempt transitions.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.17,"Workflow":0.78}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"On failed tests, refinement prompt includes failed test names and failure messages.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Slot A: \"refinement prompt builder includes the failed test names and failure messages in the next LLM prompt.\" Slot B: handoff boundary from test-result module into prompt-construction module. Slot C: if lowered to Unit, you can miss schema/field-mapping mismatches between failure payload and prompt builder input. Rejection gate: Agentic rejected because behavior text targets prompt payload composition, not quality of model judgment/output.","test_description":"Feed realistic failed-test result objects through orchestration path into prompt builder and assert next prompt contains exact failing test identifiers and messages.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.34,"Integration":0.58,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Next live attempt changes implementation in response to prior failure context, not resubmitting identical code.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"Slot A: \"next live attempt changes implementation content in response to prior failure context.\" Slot B: multi-step agentic boundary (at least two model generations with feedback-conditioned change). Slot C: if lowered to Agentic (single-step), you can miss loop-level failures where failure context is ignored and the same code is resent across attempts.","test_description":"Run real two-plus-attempt loop with captured prior failure context; assert subsequent generation is materially different from prior code and specifically addresses cited failing condition(s).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.23,"Workflow":0.7}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"After 3 failed attempts, service stops and returns structured error containing all attempts and test results.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Slot A: \"stops after 3 failed attempts and returns a structured error with all three attempts and their test results.\" Slot B: handoff/state boundary (retry counter, accumulator, and error serializer across modules). Slot C: if lowered to Unit, you can miss real aggregation/serialization mismatches where one module drops attempt data. Integration-brake: no required real OS/network; no dependence on model-output quality; no multi-step agentic correctness claim.","test_description":"Use deterministic stubs that always fail; run orchestrator and assert exactly 3 attempts executed, terminal error shape is correct, and all attempt artifacts/results are present and ordered.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.67,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"Full non-agentic pipeline wiring (generate call